channel.name: How can an update be made to the "proto-kit" to prevent arbitrage on the sequencer side in Launchpad

messages.content: For now, we don't have a chance to work on this in the short term, but we are wondering if anything is being developed for this. For now, it seems like a good idea for us to be able to solve this using Celestia.
you can route all of your transactions via L1 actions, relying on the L1 to be your mempool
alternatively you can wait for future protokit updates about MEV prevention, proposer builder separation, and shared sequencing
Can you elaborate on this a little more?
thanks to protokit's universal messaging architecture, you could provide an option to dispatch a transaction via the L1 using actions
we havent fully exposed this to developers yet, but we will pretty soon, right now the token bridge for l1<>l2 is based on this messaging architecture as well
Thank you very much, also great news, sounds good
are you building Atlaspad with Protokit?
yea
:eboTrollface:

We are considering using protokit for the early stage, in later versions we will try arbitrage in another way where the sequencer cannot be manipulated, if it cannot be prevented by the protokit itself or by us.
It's a tough challenge for us.
What exact scenarios are you considering? majority of the current EVM L2s have a centralized sequencer anyways
Unlike EVM Rollups, we want to ensure that everything can be done from a single state on MINA and increase speed and security at the same time.
i am not sure i follow 🤔

Additionally, our project has multichain compatibility. When MINA releases a stable coin (like this: https://github.com/zk0ath/usdm) we want to ensure that it can be claimed and refunded as well. What we have built is a multichain zk launchpad where arbitrage, block order, and tx reliability are not shaken. **Unlike** Lambdaclass, we want to verify a proof generated on the EVM side on the mina side. In order to be much more scalable.
(the proof of **tx** made in EVM => **Verifying in mina**  )
I think it's worth noting that the lambdaclass bridge is only from Mina to Ethereum. I.e. verifying mina inside of ethereum. The other way is not possible using this bridge
Actually, that's what I said, we want to do the opposite of what lambdaclass does.
Ah "unlike" - sorry misread
okay, i mean good luck 🙂
Thank you very much, also for your help.
Also, worth to note that even from Mina to Etherium is very expensive now.
Definitely, but evm to mina seems much cheaper compared to it
I don't know, do you have any plans on how to do it? cc: @boray
